They already have invested on curating sample images. They require an automation which can create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from a photo. DATA DESCRIPTION: The dataset comprises of images from 12 plant species. Source: https://www.kaggle.com/c/plant-seedlings-classification/data. PROJECT OBJECTIVE: To create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from a photo. Steps and tasks: [ Total Score: 30 Marks]

# 1.B.	Map the images from train folder with train labels to form a DataFrame. 
# 2.C. Unify shape of all the images:
# 2.D. Normalise all the images:

# Define the path to the train folder
train_path = 'plant-seedlings-classification/plant-seedlings-classification/train'

# Get the list of all subdirectories in the train folder
subdirs = os.listdir(train_path)

# Create an empty list to store the image data
data = []
normalized_data = []

# Loop through each subdirectory and read the images
for subdir in subdirs:
    # Get the list of all images in the subdirectory
    images = os.listdir(os.path.join(train_path, subdir))
    # Loop through each image and read it
    for image in images:
        # Read the image using OpenCV
        img = cv2.imread(os.path.join(train_path, subdir, image))

        # 2.C. Unify shape of all the images:
        # Resize the images
        img = cv2.resize(img, (128, 128))
        # Append the image data to the list
        data.append((image, subdir, img))

        # 2.D. Normalise all the images:
        # Normalize the images
        norm_img = np.zeros((128,128))
        final_img = cv2.normalize(img,  norm_img, 0, 255, cv2.NORM_MINMAX)
        # Append the image data to the list
        normalized_data.append((image, subdir, final_img))

# Convert the data list to a Pandas DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['image', 'species', 'img'])

# Convert the normalized data list to a Pandas DataFrame
normalized_df = pd.DataFrame(normalized_data, columns=['image', 'species', 'img'])

# C.	Write a function that will select n random images and display images along with its species. 
def display_random_images(df, n):
    # Select n random rows from the DataFrame
    samples = df.sample(n)
    # Loop through each row and display the image with its species
    for index, row in samples.iterrows():
        plt.imshow(row['img'])
        plt.title(row['species'])
        plt.show()

# B.	Create new CNN architecture to train the model. 

# Base model
# Define the CNN model 1

model = Sequential([
    Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 3)),
    MaxPooling2D((2,2)),  # for feature localization(detection)
    Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D((2,2)),
    Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D((2,2)),
    Conv2D(256, (3,3), activation='relu'),
    GlobalAveragePooling2D(), # reduce the dimensionality of the feature map for overall pattern
    Flatten(),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dense(12, activation='softmax') # making predictions(classification here)
])

# Compile the model
adam = optimizers.Adam(lr = 1e-3)
model.compile(optimizer=adam, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

# Define callbacks
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3, restore_best_weights=True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', patience=2, factor=0.1, min_lr=0.00001)

# C.	Train the model on train data and validate on test data. 
# Train the model
CNN_model_1 = model.fit(X_train, Y_train, epochs=20, batch_size=64, validation_data=(X_test, Y_test), shuffle=True, callbacks=[early_stop, reduce_lr], verbose = 2)

# Evaluate the model on train data
train_loss, train_acc = model.evaluate(X_train, Y_train)

Observations:¶

1) The CNN model has achieved a train accuracy of 89.73% and a test accuracy of 84.21%.

2) From the zig-zag plots, we can say that the model has overfit the training data, and as a result, the model's generalization performance is poor on test data.

3) Since our dataset is small, we can train our model on top of a Transfer Learning model that has been pre-trained on a large dataset and to improve performance. We can use the weights of the transfer learning model.

4) We can also use a larger batch size to achieve faster convergence on training data and therfore, reduce noise and overfitting on test data. But, it will lead to increased training time per epoch.

# B.	Create new CNN architecture to train the model. 

# Tranfer learning for Feature Extraction
# ResNet50 based CNN model
# Define the CNN model 2

import numpy as np
from keras.applications import ResNet50
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense, Flatten, Dropout

# Define the ResNet50 model
resnet50 = ResNet50(include_top=False, weights='imagenet', input_shape=(128, 128, 3))

# Freeze the layers in the ResNet50 model
for layer in resnet50.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

# Create a new model based on ResNet50 and add new layers
model = Sequential()
model.add(resnet50)
model.add(Flatten())

# B.	Create new CNN architecture to train the model.

# # ResNet50 based hyper-tuned CNN model
# Define the CNN model 3

import numpy as np
from keras.applications import ResNet50
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense, Flatten, Dropout
from keras import optimizers
from keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ReduceLROnPlateau
from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

# Define the ResNet50 model
resnet50 = ResNet50(include_top=False, weights='imagenet', input_shape=(128, 128, 3))

# Freeze the layers in the ResNet50 model
for layer in resnet50.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

# Create a new model based on ResNet50 and add new layers
model = Sequential()
model.add(resnet50)
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(1024, activation='elu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(512, activation='elu'))
#model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

# Fine-tune the last few layers of the ResNet50 model
for layer in resnet50.layers[-10:]:
    layer.trainable = True

# Define data generators with increased data augmentation
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rotation_range=30,
                                   zoom_range=0.3,
                                   width_shift_range=0.2,
                                   height_shift_range=0.2,
                                   shear_range=0.2,
                                   horizontal_flip=True,
                                   fill_mode='nearest')

test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator()

train_generator = train_datagen.flow(X_train, Y_train, batch_size=128)
test_generator = test_datagen.flow(X_test, Y_test, batch_size=128)

# Adjust the learning rate
opt = optimizers.Adam(lr=0.001)
#opt = SGD(lr=0.01, momentum=0.9)
model.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

# Define callbacks
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3, restore_best_weights=True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', patience=2, factor=0.1, min_lr=0.00001)

# C.	Train the model on train data and validate on test data. 
# Train the model
CNN_model_3 = model.fit(train_generator, epochs=20, steps_per_epoch=len(X_train)//128, validation_data=test_generator, 
              validation_steps=len(X_test)//128,  shuffle=True, callbacks=[early_stop, reduce_lr], verbose = 2)

# Evaluate the model on train data

# B. Train a model using any Supervised Learning algorithm and share performance metrics on test data:
def train_test_model(model, X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42):
    # Split the data into training and test sets
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=test_size, random_state=random_state)

    # Print the shape of the training and test sets
    print("Dataset shape:")
    print("*" * 50)
    print("Shape of Training Data: ", X_train.shape)
    print("Shape of Test Data: ", X_test.shape)
    print("*" * 50)

    # assign the user defined model
    model = model

    # Train the model on the training data
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Predict the labels for the test data
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    # Classification Accuracy
    print("Model Classification Accuracy:")
    print("*" * 50)
    print('Accuracy on Training data is', model.score(X_train, y_train))
    print('Accuracy on Test data is', model.score(X_test, y_test))
    print("*" * 50)

    # Print the classification report and confusion matrix
    print("\nClassification Report:\n")
    print("*" * 50)
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
    print("*" * 50)

    print("\nConfusion Matrix:\n")
    print("*" * 50)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, cmap="rainbow")
    plt.show()

# K-Fold CV for finding best Supervised Learning model
LogR_model = LogisticRegression(C=1, penalty='l2', solver='liblinear') # default parameter settings
KNN_model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=7, weights='uniform', algorithm='auto')
GN_model = GaussianNB()
svc_model_rbf = SVC(kernel='rbf', degree=2, C=10, gamma=0.1)
DT_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini', max_depth=5, min_samples_leaf=5)
RF_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_features='sqrt', max_depth=10)
XGB_model = XGBClassifier(n_estimators=100, learning_rate=0.1, max_depth=5, subsample=1, colsample_bytree=1, gamma=0, reg_alpha=0, reg_lambda=1) # default max_depth = 3

seed = 1
# prepare models
models = []
models.append(('LogR', LogR_model))
models.append(('KNN', KNN_model))
models.append(('NB', GN_model))
models.append(('SVM-rbf', svc_model_rbf))
models.append(('D-Tree', DT_model))
models.append(('RF', RF_model))
models.append(('XGB', XGB_model))

# evaluate each model in turn
results = []
names = []
scoring = 'accuracy'
for name, model in models:
    kfold = model_selection.KFold(n_splits = 10, random_state = seed, shuffle = True)
    cv_results = model_selection.cross_val_score(model, X1_PCA, Y1, cv = kfold, scoring = scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)
    
# boxplot algorithm comparison
fig = plt.figure()
fig.suptitle('Supervised Models Comparison')
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
plt.boxplot(results)
ax.set_xticklabels(names)
plt.show()

Observations:¶

2) The best performing models are --> SVM-rbf Classifier > XGB Classifier > Logistic regression.

3) The XGB classifier almost has similar accuracy to the SVM-rbf Classifier, but it also has the longest computation time of all the models.

4) Therfore, we can use the SVM-rbf Classifier on this dataset, since it has the best model performance and compute time is also less.

# Train a model on a hyper-tuned CNN and share performance metrics on test data. 

# Define the CNN model
model = Sequential()

# First convolutional layer
model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='elu', input_shape=(224,224,3)))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2,2)))
# Second convolutional layer
model.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='elu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2,2)))
# Third convolutional layer
model.add(Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='elu'))

# D.	Train a CNN model on top of Transfer Learning and share performance metrics on test data. 

import numpy as np
from keras.applications import VGG16
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense, Flatten, Dropout
from keras import optimizers, regularizers
from keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ReduceLROnPlateau
from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

# Define the CNN model
#Load the VGG model
vgg_conv = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(224, 224, 3))

# Freeze the layers in the VGG16 model
for layer in vgg_conv.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

# Create a new model based on VGG16 and add new layers
model = Sequential()
model.add(vgg_conv)
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(1024, activation='elu'))
#model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(512, activation='elu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.01)))
model.add(Dense(17, activation='softmax'))

# Freeze all the layers except for the last layer: 
for layer in vgg_conv.layers[:-4]:
    layer.trainable = False

# Define data generators with increased data augmentation
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rotation_range=30,
                                   zoom_range=0.3,
                                   width_shift_range=0.2,
                                   height_shift_range=0.2,
                                   shear_range=0.2,
                                   horizontal_flip=True,
                                   fill_mode='nearest')

test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator()

train_generator = train_datagen.flow(X_train, y_train, batch_size=32)
test_generator = test_datagen.flow(X_test, y_test, batch_size=32)

# Adjust the learning rate
opt = optimizers.Adam(lr=0.0001)
model.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

# Define callbacks
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3, restore_best_weights=True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', patience=2, factor=0.1, min_lr=0.0001)

# Train the model
CNN_classifier_3 = model.fit(train_generator, epochs=20, steps_per_epoch=len(X_train)//32, validation_data=test_generator, 
              validation_steps=len(X_test)//32,  shuffle=True, callbacks=[early_stop, reduce_lr], verbose = 2)

# Evaluate the model on train data
train_loss, train_acc = model.evaluate(X_train, y_train)
print('*' * 50)
print('Model Performance metrics on train data')
print('*' * 50)
print('Train loss:', train_loss)
print('Train accuracy:', train_acc)

# Evaluate the model on test data
test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test)
print('*' * 50)
print('Model Performance metrics on test data')
print('*' * 50)
print('Test loss:', test_loss)
print('Test accuracy:', test_acc)
print('*' * 50)

# Creating a function to compare the correctly vs misclassified images
# Import necessary libraries
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from keras.utils import to_categorical

def plot_correct_misclassified_images(model, x_test, y_test, n):
    # Get the predicted labels for test data
    pred = model.predict(x_test)
    pred_digits = np.argmax(pred, axis=1)

    # Convert test labels to categorical
    y_test_cat = to_categorical(np.argmax(y_test, axis=1))

    # Create label encoder and fit the categorical test labels
    le = LabelEncoder()
    le.fit(np.argmax(y_test_cat, axis=1))

    # Create empty lists for storing correctly and misclassified indices
    correct_indices = []
    misclassified_indices = []

    # Loop through each predicted label and compare with the true label
    for i in range(len(pred_digits)):
        if pred_digits[i] == np.argmax(y_test_cat[i]):
            correct_indices.append(i)
        else:
            misclassified_indices.append(i)

    # Plot n random correctly classified images
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(int(n/2), 2, figsize=(5, 5))
    fig.suptitle("CORRECTLY CLASSIFIED FLOWER IMAGES")
    for i, axi in enumerate(ax.flat):
        while True:
            index = np.random.randint(0, len(correct_indices))
            if index not in correct_indices[:i]:
                break
        axi.imshow(x_test[correct_indices[index]])
        axi.set_title("Predicted: {}\nTrue: {}".format(le.inverse_transform([pred_digits[correct_indices[index]]])[0], le.inverse_transform([np.argmax(y_test_cat[correct_indices[index]])])[0]))
        axi.axis('off')
        if i == n-1:
            break
    plt.tight_layout()

    # Plot n random misclassified images
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(int(n/2), 2, figsize=(5, 5))
    fig.suptitle("MISCLASSIFIED FLOWER IMAGES")
    for i, axi in enumerate(ax.flat):
        while True:
            index = np.random.randint(0, len(misclassified_indices))
            if index not in misclassified_indices[:i]:
                break
        axi.imshow(x_test[misclassified_indices[index]])
        axi.set_title("Predicted: {}\nTrue: {}".format(le.inverse_transform([pred_digits[misclassified_indices[index]]])[0], le.inverse_transform([np.argmax(y_test_cat[misclassified_indices[index]])])[0]))
        axi.axis('off')
        if i == n-1:
            break
    plt.tight_layout()
